10 percent of the total population of Jeju Province in 1947. News of this enormous loss of life was carefully suppressed until the success of the 1987 June Democracy Movement.After concisely detailing the events of Jeju 4.3, Kim traces the grassroots advocacy campaign that ultimately resulted in the creation of a truth commission with a threefold mandate: to investigate what happened in Jeju, to identify the victims, and to restore the honor of those victims. Although an official report was issued in 2003, resulting in an official apology from President Roh Moo Hyun (the first presidential apology for the abuse of state power in South Korea’s history), the commission’s work continues to this day. It has long been believed that truth commissions are most likely to be established immediately after a democratic transition, as a result of a power game involving old and new elites. Kim tells a different story: he emphasizes the importance of sixty years of local activist work and the long history of truth’s suppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMassacresxKorea (South)xCheju Island. 0aMassacreszKorea (South)zCheju Island. 0aTransitional justicexKorea (South). 0aTransitional justicezKorea (South). 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh  akorean history, korean justice system, human rights advocacy, transitional justice, counterinsurgency, korean uprising, Jeju province, mass detention, forced displacement, June Democracy Movement, asian justice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147067740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470677423Coveru